  "prompt": "What is the difference between yield stress and yield strength?",
  "response": "Yield stress and yield strength are closely related terms in materials science and engineering, but they have some subtle differences:\n\n1. Yield Stress:\n- Represents the stress at which a material begins to deform plastically\n- Typically measured in units of pressure (MPa or psi)\n- Point where elastic deformation transitions to plastic deformation\n- Directly observed from stress-strain curve\n- Specific point where permanent deformation starts to occur\n\n2. Yield Strength:\n- A more general term describing the stress required to cause permanent deformation\n- Often used interchangeably with yield stress\n- Represents the amount of stress needed to produce a specific amount of plastic strain\n- Typically defined as the stress causing 0.2% permanent strain\n- Commonly used in engineering design and material specifications\n\nKey similarities:\n- Both relate to material's plastic deformation\n- Both measured in stress units\n- Indicate transition from elastic to plastic behavior\n\nKey difference:\n- Yield stress is a precise point on the stress-strain curve\n- Yield strength is a broader concept with a conventionally defined strain offset\n\nIn practice, the terms are often used synonymously, though technically yield stress is a more precise measurement.",
